  <p>
    Septic systems don't exist in the abstract — they exist in the ground, and the ground in the Upper
    Cumberland is distinctive. Plateau rock, wooded slopes, farm hollows, clay soils, and long gravel
    drives all shape what a septic system can do and how it gets serviced. Planning that starts from
    the region's real conditions, rather than a generic template, is what keeps rural septic work from
    turning into a series of surprises.
  </p>

  {/* Intended asset: /images/resources/septic-planning-for-rural-upper-cumberland-properties-hero.webp — see public/images/resources/README.md */}
